{
  "Natural Selection and Adaptation": "自然选择和适应",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "这个课程涵盖了分析和总结数据集的中心的基本测量方法。 您将学会如何计算和应用平均值、 中位数和模式, 并了解何时最合适 。",
  "What is conservation biology?": "什么是保护生物学?",
  "Conservation biology emerged as a 'crisis discipline' in the 1980s (coined by Michael Soulé) in response to the accelerating biodiversity crisis. It is inherently interdisciplinary, combining population genetics (minimum viable population, inbreeding depression), ecology (habitat requirements, trophic cascades), biogeography (island biogeography theory, habitat fragmentation), and social sciences (environmental policy, community engagement). Unlike pure ecology, conservation biology is explicitly mission-driven — it aims to preserve biodiversity and ecosystem function.": "1980年代,养护生物学(由迈克尔·苏莱合著)作为“危机学科”出现于1980年代,以应对加速的生物多样性危机,它具有内在的跨学科性质,结合了人口遗传学(最低活人口、孕育抑郁症)、生态学(生境要求、营养级联)、生物地理学(岛屿生物地理学理论、生境分化)和社会科学(环境政策、社区参与),与纯粹的生态学不同,养护生物学是明确由使命驱动的,其目的是保护生物多样性和生态系统功能。",
  "What is sustainable development?": "什么是可持续发展?",
  "The concept was defined by the Brundtland Commission (1987) in 'Our Common Future.' Sustainable development rests on three pillars: environmental protection (maintaining ecosystem services and biodiversity), economic viability (ensuring development is economically feasible), and social equity (ensuring benefits are shared fairly). The 17 UN Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs, 2015) operationalize this concept, addressing poverty, clean water, climate action, and life on land and below water. The key challenge is decoupling economic growth from environmental degradation.": "布伦特兰委员会(1987年)在“我们的共同未来”中界定了这一概念。 可持续发展有三个支柱:环境保护(维护生态系统服务和生物多样性)、经济可行性(确保发展在经济上可行)和社会公平(确保公平分享利益 ) 。 17项联合国可持续发展目标(SDGs, 2015 ) 将这一概念付诸实施,解决贫困、清洁水、气候行动以及土地和水下生活等问题。 关键挑战是将经济增长与环境退化脱钩。",
  "What is a protected area in conservation?": "什么是养护中的保护区?",
  "Protected areas are the cornerstone of in situ conservation. The IUCN recognizes categories from strict nature reserves (Category I, minimal human use) to protected landscapes with sustainable use (Category VI). As of 2023, approximately 17% of land and 8% of oceans are in some form of protected status. The '30x30' initiative (Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework, 2022) aims to protect 30% of land and sea by 2030. Protected areas are most effective when they are large, connected by wildlife corridors, and managed with local community involvement.": "自然保护联盟承认从严格的自然保护区(第一类,最低限度的人类使用)到可持续使用受保护的景观(第六类)。 截至2023年,大约17%的土地和8%的海洋处于某种形式的受保护地位。 “30x30”倡议(Kunming-Metreal全球生物多样性框架,2022年)旨在到2030年保护30%的陆地和海洋。保护区在面积大、与野生动物走廊相连并在当地社区参与下管理时最为有效。",
  "What is restoration ecology?": "什么是恢复生态?",
  "Restoration ecology applies ecological principles to reverse environmental degradation. Techniques include removing invasive species, replanting native vegetation, reintroducing keystone species, restoring hydrology (dam removal, wetland reconstruction), and remediating contaminated soils. The UN Decade on Ecosystem Restoration (2021-2030) highlights the urgency — restoring 350 million hectares of degraded land could generate $9 trillion in ecosystem services and sequester significant carbon. Successful examples include Yellowstone wolf reintroduction, Florida Everglades restoration, and prairie reconstruction in the American Midwest.": "恢复生态学应用生态原则来扭转环境退化。技术包括清除入侵物种、重新植树本地植被、重新引进基岩物种、恢复水文(挖荒、湿地重建)和补救受污染的土壤。联合国生态系统恢复十年(2021-2030年)强调了紧迫性 — — 恢复3.5亿公顷退化土地可以产生9万亿美元生态系统服务并封存大量碳。成功的例子包括黄石狼重新引入、佛罗里达埃弗勒斯河谷恢复以及美国中西部的草原重建。",
  "What is the leading cause of species extinction worldwide?": "全世界物种灭绝的主要原因是什么?",
  "Habitat destruction is responsible for approximately 85% of species listed as threatened or endangered on the IUCN Red List. The major drivers include tropical deforestation (losing ~10 million hectares/year), conversion of grasslands and wetlands to agriculture, urbanization, and infrastructure development. Habitat fragmentation is particularly damaging because it creates isolated populations too small to be genetically viable, disrupts migration routes, and increases edge effects. The other major threats — in order — are overexploitation, invasive species, pollution, and climate change.": "生境的破坏对自然保护联盟红色清单上列为受威胁或濒危物种的大约85%负有责任,主要驱动因素包括热带砍伐森林(每年损失约1 000万公顷),将草地和湿地转为农业、城市化和基础设施发展,生境的分散性特别有害,因为它造成的孤立人口太小,无法遗传,扰乱移徙路线,并增加边际效应,其他主要威胁是过度开发、入侵物种、污染和气候变化。",
  "What is the difference between in situ and ex situ conservation?": "原地养护和原地养护有什么区别?",
  "In situ (Latin: 'in place') conservation is generally preferred because it preserves entire ecosystems, maintains natural selection, and protects ecological relationships. Examples: national parks, biosphere reserves, marine protected areas. Ex situ (Latin: 'out of place') conservation is a critical backup for species on the brink of extinction. Examples: San Diego Zoo's captive breeding of California condors, Svalbard Global Seed Vault (1 million+ seed samples), and frozen tissue repositories. The best strategies integrate both: breed in captivity (ex situ), then reintroduce to restored habitat (in situ).": "在原地(拉丁语 : “ 原地 ” ) 养护通常更受青睐, 因为它保护整个生态系统, 维持自然选择, 保护生态关系。 例如: 国家公园, 生物圈保护区, 海洋保护区。 异地( 拉丁语 : “ 原地 ” ) 养护是濒临灭绝物种的关键后盾。 例如: 圣迭戈动物园被俘的加利福尼亚神鹰繁殖, 斯瓦尔巴德全球种子洞( 100万种+种子样本) , 以及冷冻组织储存。 最佳战略结合了两种战略: 被俘( 原地 ) 繁殖, 然后重新回到恢复的生境( 原地 ) 。",
  "What is a wildlife corridor and why is it important?": "什么是野生生物走廊,为什么它重要?",
  "Wildlife corridors address one of the most harmful effects of habitat fragmentation: population isolation. When habitats become islands surrounded by development, populations become too small and inbred to be viable. Corridors allow genetic exchange, seasonal migration, range shifts in response to climate change, and recolonization after local extinctions. Examples include highway wildlife overpasses and underpasses (Banff, Canada), the Yellowstone-to-Yukon corridor (Y2Y), and riparian buffer strips along rivers. Island biogeography theory predicts that connected habitats support more species than isolated ones of equal area.": "野生生物走廊处理生境支离破碎的最有害后果之一:人口隔离。当生境成为发展环绕的岛屿时,人口就变得太小了,与世隔绝,难以生存。走廊允许基因交换、季节性移徙、针对气候变化的牧场转移以及当地灭绝之后的重新殖民化。例子包括公路野生动物过道和地下通道(加拿大,班夫)、黄石公园至尤肯走廊(Y2Y)以及沿河流的河岸缓冲带。岛屿生物地理学理论预测,连接生境的物种多于隔离的相同区域物种。",
  "What is the significance of the U.S. Endangered Species Act (ESA) of 1973?": "美国1973年《濒危物种法》(ESA)的意义是什么?",
  "The ESA is one of the world's strongest environmental laws. It has prevented the extinction of 99% of listed species, with notable successes including the bald eagle (delisted 2007), American alligator (recovered), gray wolf (controversial recovery), and peregrine falcon (delisted 1999). The ESA has two main protections: Section 7 requires federal agencies to consult with USFWS/NMFS on projects that may affect listed species; Section 9 prohibits 'take' of listed species by any person. Critical habitat designation protects the physical/biological features essential for a species' conservation.": "欧空局是世界上最强有力的环境法之一,它防止了99%的上市物种灭绝,取得了显著的成功,包括秃鹰(2007年除名)、美国鳄鱼(2007年除名)、灰狼(争议恢复)和游鹰(1999年除名)。 欧空局有两个主要保护措施:第7节要求联邦机构就可能影响上市物种的项目与美国食物安全系统/国家营养安全系统协商;第9节禁止任何人“获取”上市物种。",
  "The Florida Everglades — originally 4.3 million acres of 'River of Grass' — was reduced by 50% through drainage, agriculture, and urban development. The Comprehensive Everglades Restoration Plan (CERP, 2000) is the largest ecosystem restoration project in history, costing an estimated $23.2 billion over 35 years. The plan aims to restore natural water flow, remove invasive species, and rebuild wetland habitat. What branch of conservation science guides this project?": "Florida Everglades——最初为430万英亩的“草原”土地——通过排水、农业和城市发展减少了50%。 综合长城恢复计划(CERP,2000年)是历史上最大的生态系统恢复项目,35年来估计耗资232亿美元。 该计划旨在恢复自然水流、清除入侵物种和重建湿地生境。 哪个保护科学部门指导这个项目?",
  "CERP applies restoration ecology principles at an unprecedented scale. Key interventions include: removing 240 miles of levees and canals to restore natural sheet flow; treating agricultural runoff to reduce phosphorus pollution; controlling invasive Burmese pythons and Brazilian pepper trees; reconstructing wetland and mangrove habitats; and monitoring indicator species (wading birds, Florida panther, American crocodile). The project uses adaptive management — continuously adjusting plans based on monitoring data. Challenges include competing water demands (agriculture, urban supply), climate change (sea level rise), and political obstacles. Success would restore ecosystem services worth billions: water purification, flood protection, fisheries, and tourism.": "CERP采用前所未有的规模的恢复生态原则,主要干预措施包括:清除240英里长的流水和运河,以恢复自然床流;处理农业径流,以减少磷污染;控制侵袭的缅甸和巴西胡椒树;重建湿地和红树林生境;监测指标物种(捕鸟、佛罗里达豹、美洲鳄鱼);项目利用适应性管理——根据监测数据不断调整计划;挑战包括相互竞争的水需求(农业、城市供应)、气候变化(海平面上升)和政治障碍;成功将恢复价值数十亿的生态系统服务:净水、防洪、渔业和旅游业。",
  "The Atlantic cod fishery off Newfoundland, Canada, was one of the world's most productive fisheries for 500 years. By 1992, overfishing had collapsed the cod population to 1% of its historical size. Despite a total fishing moratorium declared that year, 30 years later the cod population has still not recovered. What does this case study teach about sustainable resource management?": "加拿大纽芬兰外的大西洋鳕鱼渔业是世界上500年来最具生产力的渔业之一,到1992年,过度捕捞使鳕鱼人口崩溃到历史规模的1%。 尽管当年宣布了全面暂停捕鱼,但30年后鳕鱼人口仍未恢复。 这个案例研究教了什么可持续资源管理?",
  "The Newfoundland cod collapse is the textbook example of un-sustainable resource exploitation. Despite warnings from scientists, political and economic pressure kept harvests above maximum sustainable yield (MSY). When the cod collapsed, a 'regime shift' occurred — the ecosystem reorganized with shrimp and crab replacing cod, and cod's prey competitors expanded to fill the niche. Young cod now face predation by species that cod once controlled. This competitive and predatory reorganization creates hysteresis — the ecosystem doesn't simply reverse when the original pressure is removed. The collapse cost 40,000 jobs and destroyed Newfoundland's economy, demonstrating that unsustainable harvesting has severe social consequences.": "纽芬兰鳕鱼的崩溃是不可持续的资源开发的典型例子。 尽管科学家们提出了警告,但政治和经济压力仍然使收获超过最高可持续产量(MSY ) 。 当鳕鱼崩溃时,出现了“制度转变 ” — —以虾和螃蟹取代鳕鱼的生态系统重组,鳕鱼的猎物竞争者也扩大了规模以填补这一空白。年轻的鳕鱼现在面临着曾经被鳕鱼控制的物种的掠夺。这种竞争和掠夺性重组造成了歇斯底里 — — 当原始压力消除时,生态系统不会简单地逆转。 崩溃花费了40,000个工作,破坏了纽芬兰的经济,表明不可持续的捕捞产生了严重的社会后果。",
  "The Svalbard Global Seed Vault, located deep inside a mountain on a Norwegian Arctic island, stores over 1.2 million seed samples from gene banks around the world. It functions as a backup in case regional seed collections are lost to natural disasters, war, equipment failure, or funding cuts. In 2015, seeds were withdrawn for the first time when Syria's gene bank was damaged by civil war. What conservation concept does this facility represent?": "位于挪威北冰洋岛屿山洞深处的斯瓦尔巴全球种子洞(Svalbard Global Seed Vault)储存了来自世界各地基因库的120多万种种子样本。 如果区域种子收集因自然灾害、战争、设备故障或资金削减而丢失,它作为备份发挥作用。 2015年,当叙利亚的基因库被内战破坏时,种子首次被提取。 这个设施代表什么保护概念?",
  "The Svalbard Seed Vault is the ultimate insurance policy for crop biodiversity. It stores seeds at -18°C in a naturally cold, dry, geologically stable location 130 meters inside a mountain. The vault's design ensures preservation even if power fails. Genetic diversity in crops is critical because: modern agriculture relies on a dangerously narrow genetic base (75% of crop diversity was lost in the 20th century); climate change requires new drought/heat-resistant varieties; and new diseases demand resistant genes that may only exist in wild relatives or traditional cultivars. The Syria withdrawal proved the vault's concept — without it, decades of agricultural research would have been irreversibly lost.": "Svalbard Seed Vault是作物生物多样性的最终保险政策,在18°C的自然寒冷、干燥、地质稳定的山中130米处储存种子。保险库的设计确保保护,即使电力失效。作物的遗传多样性至关重要,因为:现代农业依赖一个危险的狭窄基因基础(在20世纪损失了75%的作物多样性);气候变化需要新的抗旱/抗热品种;新的疾病需要只存在于野生亲戚或传统栽培者的抗病基因。叙利亚撤出证明保险库的概念 — — 没有它,几十年的农业研究将不可逆转地丧失。"
}